# Fluff Date: 2026-02-28 15:44:34
<overview>
<p>The Overlord class DropShip is one of the most recognizable and widely-produced military transport vessels in the Inner Sphere. First launched in 2762, this 9,700-ton Spheroid design quickly became the standard by which all other regiment-level Mek carriers would be judged. Produced by numerous shipyards across both the Inner Sphere and Clan space, the Overlord has served continuously for over three centuries, evidence of the fundamental soundness of its original design. Its distinctive teardrop profile and massive bay doors have become iconic symbols of military power projection throughout the BattleTech universe. Few designs have achieved such universal adoption across virtually every major military force in known space.</p><p>The sheer number of Overlords in service has made the class a common sight in virtually every major conflict since the fall of the Star League, and its continued production ensures it will remain so for the foreseeable future.</p>
</overview>

<capabilities>
<p>The A3 Overlord stands as a radical departure from the transport role, converting the hull into a pocket WarShip. All Mek bays are removed entirely, replaced by capital-grade weapons including AR-10 missile launchers on each broadside, a Kraken T missile system in the nose, and batteries of Gauss rifles, ER PPCs, and pulse lasers. Six aerospace fighter bays and three battle armor bays provide a small screening force, while 518 tons of cargo carries ammunition for the capital weapons systems.</p><p>Performance jumps dramatically with safe thrust increasing to 5, structural integrity doubled to 40, and armor coverage nearly doubling to 1,952 points of ferro-aluminum protection. The 240 double heat sinks handle the massive thermal output from sustained capital weapons fire. With a crew of 107 including 15 dedicated gunners, the A3 functions as a corvette-class combatant rather than a transport. The AR-10 launchers can fire both Barracuda and Killer Whale missiles, giving the A3 flexible anti-ship capability that can threaten vessels far above its own tonnage class. The retained fighter bays allow the A3 to operate its own combat air patrol, extending its sensor and engagement envelope.</p>
</capabilities>

<deployment>
<p>The A3 pocket WarShip emerged from the development of DropShip-scale capital weapons platforms during the late 3050s. First deployed in 3058, the design saw action during the FedCom Civil War and the Jihad, where its capital-grade weapons gave DropShip formations a credible anti-WarShip capability without the expense and vulnerability of dedicated WarShip assets. Several major military powers adopted the A3 as a cost-effective way to project naval power, particularly after the devastating WarShip losses of the Jihad made replacement hulls increasingly scarce.</p>
</deployment>

<history>
<p>The Overlord class DropShip traces its origins to the height of the Star League era, when the Star League Defense Force recognized the need for a standardized heavy Mek transport capable of deploying a full battalion in a single vessel. Previous designs had forced commanders to split their forces across multiple smaller transports, complicating coordination during contested landings. The Overlord was designed from the ground up to solve this problem, with bay capacity for thirty-six BattleMeks and integral aerospace fighter support.</p><p>Entering service in 2762, the Overlord quickly proved its worth during the Amaris Civil War, where SLDF forces used the design extensively during the liberation of Terra. The ability to land an entire battalion in a single drop, supported by its own fighter screen and considerable defensive armament, gave the Overlord a decisive advantage in contested planetary assaults. When Aleksandr Kerensky led the Exodus, hundreds of Overlords accompanied the SLDF fleet into the unknown.</p><p>The Succession Wars that followed the Star League's collapse only increased the Overlord's importance. As JumpShip numbers dwindled and each transit became more precious, the ability to move a full battalion on a single docking collar became even more valuable. Production continued at reduced rates throughout the Succession Wars, and captured Overlords were among the most prized spoils of war. The Clans independently developed the Overlord C variant, scaling the hull up to 11,600 tons to carry forty-five Meks organized in the Clan Trinary structure.</p><p>The Clan Invasion of 3049 prompted the first major refit of the Inner Sphere Overlord in centuries. The 3056 variant replaced aging autocannons with Gauss rifles and upgraded energy weapons to their ER equivalents, dramatically improving the design's ability to survive contested drops against Clan-grade opposition. The Word of Blake Jihad later spawned the A3 and A3A pocket WarShip conversions, mounting capital-grade weapons on the proven Overlord hull.</p><p>Today the Overlord remains in widespread service across virtually every major military force in the Inner Sphere and Clan space. Its longevity is a reflection of the soundness of the original Star League design, and continued production ensures the class will remain the backbone of military DropShip fleets for decades to come.</p>
</history>

